  "transcript": {
    "language": "en",
    "is_generated": true,
    "source": "whisper_local",
    "segments": [
      {
        "start": 0.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "Hello, wordsmiths and welcome to Eat Your Words, the Vocabulary Cooking Show."
      },
      {
        "start": 5.0,
        "duration": 2.0,
        "text": "I'm your host, David from Khan Academy."
      },
      {
        "start": 7.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "And folks, let me tell you we have such a wonderful menu for this video."
      },
      {
        "start": 11.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "On the menu are essential, modify, advance, and longevity."
      },
      {
        "start": 16.0,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "We'll talk about what these words mean and their word parts and then we'll use them in some sentences."
      },
      {
        "start": 22.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "Essential is an adjective that means necessary or extremely important."
      },
      {
        "start": 27.0,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "Modify is a verb, it means to change usually to improve something."
      },
      {
        "start": 33.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "Advance, another verb, it means to move forward to improve or to put forward an idea."
      },
      {
        "start": 40.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "And longevity is a noun that means long life or the quality of being long-lasting."
      },
      {
        "start": 47.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "Let's talk about the recipes for these words, what goes into them?"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "Well, essential comes from the Latin verb essay meaning to be."
      },
      {
        "start": 56.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "You can see this in both Spanish and French in the verbs est-ar, and etch,"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "or more obviously in the Italian est-ar, all of them mean to be."
      },
      {
        "start": 66.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "So something that is essential is necessary for existing, for being."
      },
      {
        "start": 71.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "A related word in English is essence, like the true nature or the most basic version of a thing."
      },
      {
        "start": 78.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "Modify comes from mod meaning manner or way, to modify something is to change the way it works."
      },
      {
        "start": 85.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "Advance is a funny one because of that D, it actually comes from AB plus anti."
      },
      {
        "start": 92.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "So AB in Latin means from and anti means before or in front of."
      },
      {
        "start": 96.0,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "So to advance is to move forward, to go before everyone else by being in front."
      },
      {
        "start": 102.0,
        "duration": 3.0,
        "text": "So AB, not AD, meaning to."
      },
      {
        "start": 105.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "My word origin says that the D sound came into English as a mistake,"
      },
      {
        "start": 109.0,
        "duration": 3.0,
        "text": "that it was written in English as AD and not AB."
      },
      {
        "start": 112.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "It doesn't really affect the meaning, it's just a historical oddity."
      },
      {
        "start": 116.0,
        "duration": 2.0,
        "text": "Anti shows up in a lot of English words."
      },
      {
        "start": 118.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "There's Anticipate, which is to wait for something that hasn't happened yet."
      },
      {
        "start": 122.0,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "There's Ancestor, which comes from the Latin Antisessor, one who has gone before you."
      },
      {
        "start": 128.0,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "Antiscedent is a grammar term for the noun that a pronoun replaces."
      },
      {
        "start": 133.0,
        "duration": 3.0,
        "text": "It's the word you said before."
      },
      {
        "start": 136.0,
        "duration": 2.0,
        "text": "I ate the apple."
      },
      {
        "start": 138.0,
        "duration": 2.0,
        "text": "It was delicious."
      },
      {
        "start": 140.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "Antiscedent of it is Apple, because I said Apple first."
      },
      {
        "start": 144.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "I said Apple before it, but both words refer to the same thing."
      },
      {
        "start": 148.0,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "Long Jeviti comes from a Latin root long, which big surprise means long,"
      },
      {
